	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>‘Aid for trade’ may help ACP fish producers improve quality </h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 August 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Participants at a recent meeting organised by ICTSD and UNEP discussed how best to create value and improve development opportunities through trade in the fisheries sector, while safeguarding severely threatened resources. The biological limits of the fisheries themselves, and the need to manage them sustainably, were acknowledged. With regard to market access, participants provided examples of how difficult sanitary regulations can be to fulfil, as well as other requirements, such as those related to rules of origin. </p><p>Participants also discussed the role of aid for trade in this regard, and whether targeted aid for trade could help developing countries overcome barriers and more successfully add value to their exports in the fish sector. The example was given of ACP fish products which increasingly face quality-related standards and requirements such as the traceability of fish. The executive secretary of the Lake Victoria Fisheries Organisation (LVFO) argued that, ‘small-scale fishers can participate in the globalised markets if they address international market requirements such as labelling and sanitary and phyto-sanitary measures. Most developing countries are still busy fighting these measures. But if you get there first and work hard, you can meet the requirements. While the equipment may be different to that used in rich countries it does not mean that poor countries cannot comply.’ </p><p>He further explained: ‘We have canoes – not at the level of big vessels, but with the same standard of hygiene. These canoes are easy to clean and they can carry ice. I don’t buy it when some developing countries claim that they cannot comply with international standards. Uganda, Kenya and Tanzania have developed laboratories, both private and public, and they can meet the requirements of certification and export internationally.’ </p><p>Mauritius is another one of the members of the Common Market for East and Southern Africa (COMESA) that have harmonised their rules to export internationally. ‘Whether you are small or big, you want to move up the value chain,’ stated the representative of the permanent mission of Mauritius in Geneva. Mauritius has pushed for aid for trade not only for infrastructure but to meet the high standards imposed on the fisheries sector.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
ICTSD Meeting on Fisheries, Trade and Development, co-organised with UN Environment Programme, 16 June 2010<br />
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/events/dialogues/75670/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/events/dialogues/75670/</a></p><p>
Press article, ‘Help small fishers fish less, earn more’, IPS, 21 June 2010<br />
<a href="http://www.ipsnews.net/africa/nota.asp?idnews=51891" target="_self">http://www.ipsnews.net/africa/nota.asp?idnews=51891</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>As highlighted by the Lake Victoria Fisheries Organisation, rather than fighting trade-related standards, a better path to follow for ACP countries wanting to export to international markets such as the EU would be to work to comply with international requirements. This being said, it is also important to ensure that the obligation is to comply with the objectives of the standards, and not necessarily on the procedures. All too often the emphasis in market states’ requirements, the EU IUU or SPS regulations for example, is placed on the procedure, which involves a lot of bureaucracy, and puts some ACP producers, especially small-scale enterprises, at an unfair disadvantage. Using aid for trade to help meet international standards, as done by Mauritius, is an example worth looking into for ACP countries.</p>
		</div>
		
